### 1.4 Case Study: Operation Phish Phry (2009)

**Incident:**
- Egyptian cybercrime ring compromised 100+ US banks
- Used stolen credentials to initiate calls from bank PBX systems
- Routed calls to premium numbers in Egypt & UAE
- Total loss: $1.2 million in 6 months

**Detection Failure:**
- Banks didn't monitor international call patterns
- No alerts for overnight calling spikes
- Fraud discovered only after customer complaints

**Lessons Learned:**
- Real-time call analytics are essential
- Whitelist-based international calling (opt-in for businesses)
- Two-factor auth for PBX admin access

### 1.5 Countermeasures

**Preventive:**
- [ ] Implement international dialing blocks by default
- [ ] Require manual approval for high-cost destinations
- [ ] Set per-account spending thresholds ($100/day)

**Detective:**
- [ ] Real-time CDR monitoring with < 30 sec alerts
- [ ] Daily reports of international call spikes
- [ ] Cross-reference with customer profile (does user travel?)

**Responsive:**
- [ ] Auto-block after 3 consecutive calls to same premium destination
- [ ] Customer SMS notification for any international call > $10
- [ ] Fraud team escalation within 15 minutes

